review_blob: UPDATED: MAY 21, 2014
beer_name: Rogue New Crustacean Barleywineish Imperial IPA Sorta

review_blob: Can. Pours an opaque jet black with a small amount of mocha head. Aroma and taste are sweet booze, roasted malts, and chocolate. By far the best canned beer I've had.

2010 bottle from BevMo. Poured a nice rich caramel brown with rapidly dissipating off-white head. Wonderful vanilla and bourbon flavor, which increases as it warms. Notes of pitted fruit, earth, and bread in the aroma. Delicious!
beer_name: Widmer Brothers Reserve Barrel Aged Brrrbon

review_blob: 12oz can from Total Wine. Pours a hazy amber orange with some foamy white head. Citrus aroma with some pine notes. Balanced taste with a nice hoppy bite. Pretty good and a great value.
beer_name: Joseph James Hop Box Imperial IPA

review_blob: 22oz bomber. Deep black color with a foamy mocha head. Sweet, malt aroma. Sweet, yet slightly hoppy, flavor with a hint of floral and licorice. Decent but didn't blow me away.
beer_name: 10 Barrel / Bluejacket / Stone Suede Imperial Porter

review_blob: Bomber from TW&M, Peoria. Pours a rich amber with plenty of off-white head. Aroma is sweet and bready, taste is malty up front with a mellow hoppy finish. Decent.
beer_name: BrewDog Old World India Pale Ale

review_blob: 22oz waxed bomber. Pours a clear amber with little head. Aroma is raisin and some other dark fruit, with a faint hint of whisky. Taste is a little bready and without much character. Not blown away by any means.

Corked and capped 750ml bottled 4/20/12. Pours an opaque orange with plenty of eggshell head. Aroma is bready, sweet, apricot, pitted fruit, and citrusy hops. Taste is even and balanced, with a nice hoppy bite.
beer_name: Uinta Detour Double India Pale Ale

review_blob: Hello, 911? I'd like to report an assault! A whole gang of hops is beating the senses out of my face!!

22oz bomber of '12, bottled July 19, 2012. Pours a hazy amber-orange with minimal head. Sweet boozy aroma with pitted fruit, bread malt, caramel, and some earthy hops. Taste is very balanced, a bit more hop-forward than the aroma. No hot spots at all; ages well. Delicious!
22oz bomber from AJ's Market. Super smoky, peaty aroma and taste. Tasty, but absolutely no hint of the Old Guardian in there (except for alcohol content).
Light yellow pour with little head. Sweet honey and earth aroma. Crisp, sweet flavor. Pretty refreshing here in AZ on an 118-degree day.
On tap at the Gordon Ramsay pub in Caesar's Palace, LV. Nice vanilla notes from the oak in both the taste and aroma. Good.
22oz bomber of unknown vintage. Pours a dark opaque brown with very little head. Aroma is very sweet, with pitted fruit most prominent. Taste is also sweet and malty. Very little hop flavor.
beer_name: Marin Old Dipsea Barleywine Style Ale

review_blob: 22oz bomber, bottling no. 13.  Pours a rich mahogany with light mocha head that dissipates quickly. Aroma is sweet, boozy, and slightly earthy. Some oak, vanilla, and bourbon notes come through as it warms. Oak definitely present in the taste, with bourbon, pitted fruit, and vanilla notes. Great, complex barley wine.
22oz bottled 2/2013. Pours a pale orange. Big citrus hop aroma, with a big citrus taste. Yummy!

Unknown vintage, but the bottle reads "10D" in a label box. Tasted side by side with a 2013 Bigfoot. Nice, rich amber color with plenty of eggshell head, just a hair darker than the BF. Aroma is deep caramel, sweet and boozy, less hoppy than the BF.  Some dark cherry, sweet tea, and bourbon notes come out in the aroma as it warms. Taste is an excellent balance of malt and hops, with no spikes at all.

Pours a reddish amber with lots of carbonation. Head dissipates rapidly, and so does the carbonation. Aroma is heavy strawberry, but like dried strawberries or strawberry shortcake. A bit of honey in the aroma. Taste is sweet, then tart, with a thin mouthfeel. Reminds me a bit of what a strawberry lambic would taste like. Very easy to drink, especially since it is 97 degrees here today. Pretty refreshing, and much less disgusting than many of the reviews implied.

2012 vintage to a red wine glass. Pours a very dark brown, but not quite pitch black. Chocolate mill head with many boulders, and rapidly receding. Aroma is earthy and rich, with some floral notes. Taste is complex, as are most DFH beers. Toasty malts, some sweetness from the honey, with a crisp finish. Good.

22oz bomber of unknown vintage. Pours an opaque amber with minimal off-white head that quickly dissipates. Aroma is citrus (mainly lemon), booze, floral hops, and bread. Taste is hoppy, but with a nice malt balance. A bit hot, but not too bad. Floral finish. Not as good as their Imperial Stout, but an excellent ABW.
beer_name: Beer Valley Highway To Ale Barley Wine

review_blob: Golden, almost amber color with eggshell head. Citrusy hop aroma with some pitted fruit. Big taste, similar to the aroma.  Does not disappoint.
beer_name: Beer Valley Leafer Madness Imperial Pale Ale

review_blob: 2013 release. Slightly opaque brown with some tan head that lasts. Very hoppy aroma for a barley wine, mostly pine, but with some caramel and vanilla malt notes. Taste is more hop forward also. Great beer now, but I would definitely like to taste it aged.

Pours a dark brown, almost coffee, color with fast-receding tan head. Malty, sweet, alcohol forward aroma, with some toffee notes. Taste is sweet with toffee and alcohol most prominent. Smooth finish and silky mouth feel. Good beer.
2013 reserve from TW&B. Nice rich brown color with some tan head. Nice lacing. Aroma is heavy vanilla, oak, booze, coconut, tobacco, and the taste is pretty similar. Good stuff.

22oz bottle, 2012 reserve. Pours an opaque mahogany with a small amount of tan head. Aroma is sweet and boozy, with dark cherry, bread, and a little tobacco. Hops definitely come through in the taste, but it is still pretty balanced. I have nothing bad to say about this ABW.

22oz bomber, 18th Anniversary, bottled on March 21, 2012.  Pours a slightly opaque amber close to a caramel apple. Virtually no head. Aroma is pretty mellow, perhaps because of a year in the cellar.  Taste is mellow and very even, no hot spots at all.  Both the taste and aroma have subtle vanilla notes, with a nice hop finish. This beer aged very well. Spectacular.
beer_name: Great Divide Anniversary Wood Aged Double IPA

review_blob: 22oz bottle, 2012 release. Pours an opaque amber with quickly receding tan head. Aroma is boozy with pitted fruits and citrus hops. Not surprisingly (since it is a Stone beer), the taste is boldly hopped. Silky mouth feel. Delicious.

750ml bottle to a wine glass. Pours a clear pale yellow with a small amount of white head. Aroma is sweet grapes and must. Taste is sweet and slightly funky, in a good way. I am not the most familiar with the Saison style, but this is a tasty beer.
12 oz bottle. Pours very dark brown, with a small amount of mocha head. Sweet aroma, thin taste.
22oz bomber, 2011 release. Dark ruby color with virtually no head. Sweet, boozy aroma with notes of pitted fruit and molasses. Taste is similar. Pretty good.
beer_name: Alaskan Pilot Series: Barley Wine Ale

review_blob: 22oz bomber, bottled June 5, 2012. Pours amber with quickly fading eggshell head. Aroma is booze and citrus, with a hint of bready esters. Taste is hop forward, with a nice smooth mouth feel. A hint of grapefruit comes through in the taste as it warms. A wonderful IIPA.

12oz bottle from TW&B. Bottled 10/12/12. Pours a rich mahogany, slightly opaque, with no head. Nice boozy aroma, with nice notes of sherry and bread esters. Taste is complex with a great hoppy bite. Notes of gingerbread, booze, and sherry. Delicious!!

22oz bomber, release # 9 (Nov. 2012), 10.6% abv. Pours an opaque amber, slightly orange. No head. Aroma is mainly alcohol and bready yeast, taste is the same. Just not a very complex beer. Not the best ABW I'have had, but not the worst either.

22oz bomber bottled December 2011.  Pours a rich mahogany, slightly opaque, with a rapidly dissipating eggshell head. Aroma is sweet and alcohol forward, with some piney hops, caramel, and pitted fruit. Taste is similar to the aroma, but hoppier.  Mouth feel is smooth. Ages well. Very smooth.
On tap at Johnny Fox's. Copper color with nice frothy head that lingers. Very floral hoppy taste. Great IPA.

2012 bottle from TW&B Glendale. Pours a rich copper with an off white foamy head. Aroma is not as hoppy as I expected, and is mainly bread malts and some citrusy hops. Taste is flip-flopped from the aroma, with much more hops than malt. A nice, fresh hop flavor with mellow pine and citrus. The grapefruit ramps up in the taste as it warms. Delicious!
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Harvest Wet Hop IPA - Northern Hemisphere

review_blob: 12oz bottle to a snifter. Nice reddish amber color. Aroma is hoppy, mainly grapefruit. Taste is sharp and hoppy, more piney that the aroma.

12oz bottle to a snifter. Nice amber pour with little head. Hoppy aroma, much more than the taste. Taste is a nice balance of hoppy fruit and floral notes and some sweet honey.  Bitterness on the finish is great. Delicious!!

22oz bomber, bottled November 14, 2011. Pours jet black with a mocha head that sticks around. Rich malty and sweet aroma. Taste has more of a bite than its non-aged brother, almost a spicy note. A little vanilla from the oak, and some roast and earth in the finish. The first time I had this over s year ago, it was spectacular. But the flavor definitely evens out after about 15 months of aging.  So, it is now spectacular + 1.
beer_name: Great Divide Yeti Imperial Stout - Oak Aged

review_blob: 22oz bomber to a red wine glass. Pours jet black with some mocha head that rapidly dissipates. Aroma is alcohol forward, with bready malt overtones. Taste is gigantic, sweet alcohol explosion with plum and raisin on the finish. Overall, pretty complex for 16%. Happy birthday!
22oz bomber from AJ's on Camelback. Pours a hazy orange with plenty of eggshell head. Aroma is fruity and floral, and the taste had that Belgian tang. A nice match of hoppy IPA and a Belgian.

750ml corked and caged, from TW&B in Glendale. Bottled on June 22, 2012. Pours an opaque brown, very deep and rich. Tan head with some boulders. Aroma is sweet and complex malts, with some bourbon and dark fruit. The bourbon, vanilla and oak really start to shine through as it warms.  Goes really well with a piece of dark chocolate! Overall, a beautifully well-executed American Barley Wine with a sophisticated taste.

12 oz bottle from AJ's on Camelback. 2012 vintage. Pours a rich, clear brown with virtually no head. Aroma is sweet and boozy, with a good amount of figs and dates.  Taste is also sweet and boozy. Overall this is similar to 120 Minute, but the aroma and taste is much more complex and balanced.

22oz bomber from Jubilation on a recent trip to Albuquerque.  Gold wax cap, no year otherwise indicated. Pours a deep, opaque brown with a small head that rapidly dissipates. Aroma is sweeter than the Chicken Killer (if that is possible), with lots of whiskey and vanilla. Taste is a bit sour and more complex than the Chicken Killer and has plenty of oak notes, bourbon, dark fruits, and caramel. This is a pretty good variation.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

22oz bomber from Jubilation on a recent trip to Albuquerque.  Pours a deep, opaque brown with a small head that rapidly dissipates. Aroma is sweet and boozy, with some dark fruit and caramelized sugar. Taste is milder than the aroma, and crisp on the palate with a boozy aftertaste. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Santa Fe Chicken Killer Barley Wine

review_blob:
750ml bottle to a pilsner glass. Pours a nice golden yellow, with a foamy head and good carbonation. Perhaps a bit richer color than a traditional pils. Aroma has a good mix of malt and some fruity hops. Taste is a great punch of traditional pils, hops, and alcohol. Delicious! 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

12oz bottle. Pours a nice mahogany brown, with plenty of creamy head. Aroma is bread, yeast, and some spice. Taste is sweet raisin, earth, burnt sugar, and some alcohol. Crisp mouth feel with a nice body. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

12 oz bottle to a glass. Pours a rich ruddy brown with very little head. Very malty aroma, with hints of straw, earth and spice. Complex, malty taste.  The spice of the rye comes through more in the taste. Surprisingly complex beer, in a great way. Delicious. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

12oz bottle. Pours a golden yellow, like a lager. Small amount of head that quickly dissipates. Aroma is sweet muscat grapes, taste is a mix of muscat and honey. Very sweet, but good overall. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Dogfish Head Midas Touch Golden Elixir

review_blob:
22oz waxed bomber from AJ's. Pours a dark, deep brown just shy of black. Creamy head that recedes quickly. Roasted coffee aroma. Taste is also heavy coffee, and lighter bodied than I was expecting. I feel that it could perhaps have a bit more alcohol to balance out the joe. Overall, pretty good. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
